&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #1:&amp;nbsp; Please explain in detail the reasoning behind the "100% / 64% / 47%" ratio for cleric/druid/shaman heals?&amp;nbsp; Also comment on whether this is expected to continue as is?&amp;nbsp; And why is this ratio not also applied to our 10-second "incomplete heal" spells as well?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The ratios are now:&amp;nbsp; "100% / 75% / 65%".&amp;nbsp; Certainly a dramatic improvement for shamans.&amp;nbsp; But we still do not have an explanation regarding the reasoning for why this ratio is what it is.&amp;nbsp; Now, if our 10-second heal followed this same ratio, it would heal for 4875 hp and actually be usable rather than laughed at and dumped on page 50 of the spellbook to gather dust.&amp;nbsp; In my opinion, this question, updated with the more recent ratios, is still fairly interesting.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #2:&amp;nbsp; Please explain the role you expect for shaman to fill in groups fighting mobs which mitigate slows, since the way slow mitigation was implemented decreases our already marginal advantage over other slowing classes?&amp;nbsp; Please explain how you expect shamans to carry out that role (perhaps an example which includes mana spent, time spent, damage mitigated, damage dealt, and so on, along with a situation where we are the best choice class to fill that role)&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Still seems like a moderately interesting question.&amp;nbsp; They've mitigated slows and then made resist-adjusted slows available to the other slowing classes.&amp;nbsp; As time goes on, slows continue their trend of becoming interchangeable.&amp;nbsp; This is clearly good for other classes when they want to make groups, since they can just grab whichever "slower" says yes first.&amp;nbsp; But it's actually gotten to the point where slows are very heavily mitigated in some content.&amp;nbsp; In that content, a second healer can heal back more damage versus an unslowed mob than our slows prevent.&amp;nbsp; In other words, they've effectively made it so that 6 classes can fill that one group slot (shm, enc, bst, brd, dru, cle) once slows are heavily mitigated.&amp;nbsp; This is my analysis of the situation.&amp;nbsp; Still would be nice to hear the answer from the people who actually control these class balance issues.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #3:&amp;nbsp; In a full raid of 72 people, one would expect there to be 4-5 shamans, assuming classes are in balance and about equally represented.&amp;nbsp; What is your vision of what shamans #3, #4, and #5 should be doing on a raid?&amp;nbsp; How is shaman #3-#5 better than having cleric #6,#7,#8 or wizard #6,#7,#8?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Maybe current&amp;nbsp;end game raids have something useful for the Nth shaman to do, but most of the raids through PoTime do not.&amp;nbsp; In most of those raids that I've attended, the raid would have been much better off with an extra cleric.&amp;nbsp; Again, this was written from the point of view of the "average" raid scene 18 months ago.&amp;nbsp; Not today's.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #4:&amp;nbsp; If a group already has sufficient healing and a slower, but invites a shaman nevertheless, how much worse is that shaman's target DPS than say adding a wizard?&amp;nbsp; magician?&amp;nbsp; beastlord?&amp;nbsp; paladin?&amp;nbsp; necro?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;This is still a perfectly valid question.&amp;nbsp; What exactly is our target DPS&amp;nbsp;relative to other classes&amp;nbsp;when doing nothing else?&amp;nbsp; Anecdotal claims that one shaman in one situation can achieve a peak of some large amount of DoT damage for a single tick doesn't really answer the question.&amp;nbsp; Nor does hand-wavy discussions of panther.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #5:&amp;nbsp; If stat buffs are supposed to actually do something, please explain to us what going from 250 to 350 in each stat is supposed to do and under what conditions stat buffs should actually be used?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;This is also still a fairly valid question for many shamans.&amp;nbsp; Not everyone has the level 66+ buffs that have non-stat increases.&amp;nbsp; There are still some people playing at lower levels.&amp;nbsp; And there are still some few people whose stats aren't maxed out.&amp;nbsp; Understanding what the stats are really supposed to do would still be useful.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #6:&amp;nbsp; Please tell us why DoTs have gone from being more efficient and yielding more damage than the best nukes in the game&amp;nbsp;to their present state of less damage, more agro, less efficiency, and fights that don't last for their entire duration?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;This is still a very valid question.&amp;nbsp; The previous responder clearly didn't bother doing his homework if he thinks i'm comparing unfocussed to focussed or whatnot.&amp;nbsp; Looking at just raw lucy numbers:&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Sisslak = 578 * 5 = 2890 dmg for 609 mana (4.75 dmg/mana).&amp;nbsp; Gelidan Comet = 3385 for 650 mana (5.2 dmg/mana).&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Back in the old days, our DoTs were more mana efficient and did more total damage than the best nukes in the game.&amp;nbsp; It just took longer.&amp;nbsp; Now they are less mana efficient and do less damage.&amp;nbsp; The question is quite valid.&amp;nbsp; Also, even our curse DoTs are not fast enough to finish in a lot of content, so become even less mana efficient and do less total dmg.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #7:&amp;nbsp; Please tell us under exactly what conditions rabid bear is supposed to be useful?&amp;nbsp; And why its extreme power indicates a base reuse time of 2+ hours.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;This AA is still a pointless toy.&amp;nbsp; We could have it on 100% of the time and still would suck at melee.&amp;nbsp; I'd like an explanation of why such a piece of crap is cluttering up my AA choices rather than something that's actually useful.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #8:&amp;nbsp; Please tell us who most of our alchemy made potions are supposed to be used by and under what conditions?&amp;nbsp; The please justify the current prices.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Also still a perfectly valid question.&amp;nbsp; Why waste developer effort enhancing a skill that produces mostly useless crap.&amp;nbsp; Yes, it applies to a lot of trade skills, but the question is still valid regarding alchemy in particular.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #9:&amp;nbsp; Please tell us why malos has such a large cast/recast&amp;nbsp;tiime, since given that almost none of our spells have innate resist adjustments we're clearly expected to cast it on most mobs before casting damage spells.&amp;nbsp; Most other classes have damage spells with innate resist modifiers, even if they have damage spells with resist adjustments.&amp;nbsp; (See druids with -50 on their much more efficient rain spell&amp;nbsp;despite having a cold debuf spell&amp;nbsp;as an example.)&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;This is also still a very valid question.&amp;nbsp; And as I said 18 months ago, I don't really much care about the anecdotal opinion of some random person.&amp;nbsp; These questions are for the devs.&amp;nbsp; Brenlo claimed he would get us answers.&amp;nbsp; Still waiting....&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT color=#33cc00&gt;QUESTION #10:&amp;nbsp; Please explain why it would be a game altering change to allow shaman pets to have innate SoW?&amp;nbsp; Innate dual wield?&amp;nbsp; Or even why you don't just add an item that summons pet usable junk weapons so we can be spared the frustration of realizing we forgot to restock our backpack full of rusty daggers before crawling all the way to some out of the way GoD zone?&amp;nbsp; While you're at it, explain where our pets are supposed to be in the DPS and surviveability hierarchies of the other pet classes?&amp;nbsp; Are our pets supposed to lose to lower level SK pets?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The dual wield part of this is now irrelevent.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; But where our pet is supposed to be in terms of dps and survivability is still a perfectly interesting and valid question.&amp;nbsp; Our AAs are cluttered up with marginally useful pet AA, sort of implying we're a pet class, but then we don't have access to pet focus items.&amp;nbsp; It's all very confusing.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;If I were to write a new "10 questions" list, these might not be them, but they're not that far off.&amp;nbsp; But I'm unlikely to bother given that these haven't even had a whiff of an answer in over a year from anyone other than random people who are bored and either happy or disgruntled, but either way totally biased.&amp;nbsp; The unbiased dev answer would be a lot more enlightening.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by GlowingRune on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;08-24-2005&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;01:02 PM&lt;/span&gt;</description>
